article.description: Roneeka Hodges had 16 points as LSU routed Southwest Texas State for the second time this season.
article.headline: LSU keeps on its roll with 36-point victory
article.linkText: Top-seeded LSU breezes through first-round encounter
article.story:
EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- They hadn't played for a while, so the Louisiana State Lady Tigers needed a victory like this one.

	   Roneeka Hodges had 16 points as the West Region's top-seeded
team routed Southwest Texas State 86-50 Saturday night to advance
to the second round of the NCAA Tournament.

	   LSU, which upset favorite Tennessee in the SEC tournament final
back March 9 to earn a top seed for the first time in school
history, led by as many as 38 points and simply overwhelmed the
Bobcats (18-14).

	   It was much the same earlier this season, when LSU routed
Southwest Texas 91-40 in Baton Rouge. LSU led that one
by as many as 55.

	   The Lady Tigers (28-3) will meet eighth-seeded Wisconsin-Green
Bay on Monday night at McArthur Court. The Phoenix beat Washington
78-65 in the earlier first-round game.

	   ''It was a good effort and I was pleased with that,'' LSU coach
Sue Gunter said. ''We were a little bit rusty but we got a good
performance out of a lot of people.''

	   Guard Seimone Augustus, the SEC freshman of the year, put the
Lady Tigers up 26-13 in the first half with an easy layup and LSU
simply piled on more points from there, taking a 47-25 lead into
halftime.

	   Augustus finished with 11 points.

	   Doneeka Hodges, Roneeka's twin sister, nailed a jumper on a fastbreak that made the lead 66-35 midway through the second half.

	   LSU shot 65.4 percent from the floor.

	   ''I don't know if there's too many people who can stop our
offense,'' LSU guard Temeka Johnson said.

	   The Bobcats were led by Southland Conference player of the year
Tori Talbert, who had 18 points and 11 rebounds. She averaged 15.9
points and a conference-leading 12.1 rebounds a game this season.

	   During a second-half timeout, Talbert tried to keep her
teammates into the game by clapping and cheering, ''Let's go!''

	   Afterward she said the Bobcats never gave up.

	   ''I didn't feel overwhelmed and I don't think we felt
overwhelmed as a team,'' Talbert said. ''I think we got behind, we
started rushing things, started forcing shots and not playing the
type of basketball that got us here.''

	   Southwest Texas closed out the regular season with seven
consecutive victories, including the conference tournament final against
Texas-San Antonio, to earn the school's second NCAA bid. Their only
other appearance came in 1997 with a first-round defeat against Texas.

	   The Lady Tigers lost to just three teams during the regular
season -- Arkansas, Tennessee and Vanderbilt -- then beat all three
in the SEC tournament to finish the regular season ranked No. 3.
